# Cursor Rules for Jekyll Project

## Project Overview
- **Framework**: Jekyll static site generator
- **Style**: Business/Professional
- **Purpose**: Template landing page
- **Repository**: GitHub
- **Deployment**: AWS S3 static site hosting with CloudFront CDN and SSL
- **CI/CD**: GitHub Actions workflows
- **Environments**: Development (dev) and Production (prod)

## Language Requirements
- Code comments in English
- Variable names and function names can in English (standard practice)

## Jekyll Best Practices
- Use Jekyll 4.x or latest stable version
- Follow Jekyll directory structure conventions:
  - `_config.yml` for site configuration
  - `_posts/` for blog posts (if applicable)
  - `_layouts/` for layout templates
  - `_includes/` for reusable components
  - `_sass/` for Sass partials
  - `assets/` for CSS, JS, images
- Use Liquid templating language correctly
- Optimize for static site generation
- Use Jekyll plugins sparingly and document them

## Code Style & Structure
- Use semantic HTML5
- Follow BEM methodology for CSS class naming (or similar)
- Use SCSS/Sass for stylesheets
- Keep JavaScript modular and minimal (prefer vanilla JS or lightweight frameworks)
- Use meaningful variable and function names
- Maintain consistent indentation (2 spaces for YAML, 2-4 spaces for HTML/CSS/JS)

## Business Style Guidelines
- Professional, clean, modern design
- Focus on clarity and conversion
- Ensure responsive design (mobile-first approach)
- Accessible design (WCAG 2.1 AA compliance)
- Clear call-to-action buttons
- Professional typography

## AWS Deployment Configuration
- S3 bucket configuration:
  - Static website hosting enabled
  - Proper bucket policies for CloudFront access
  - Environment-specific buckets (dev/prod)
- CloudFront distribution:
  - SSL/TLS certificate (ACM)
  - Custom domain configuration
  - Caching policies optimized for static content
  - Error pages configuration
- Environment variables:
  - Use separate S3 buckets for dev and prod
  - Use different CloudFront distributions per environment
  - Configure via GitHub Actions secrets or GitLab CI variables

## CI/CD Workflow Requirements
- **GitHub Actions** (if using GitHub):
  - Workflow files in `.github/workflows/`
  - Separate workflows for dev and prod deployments
  - Build Jekyll site before deployment
  - Deploy to appropriate S3 bucket based on branch/environment
  - Invalidate CloudFront cache after deployment
- **GitLab CI** (if using GitLab):
  - `.gitlab-ci.yml` in project root
  - Separate stages for dev and prod
  - Use GitLab CI variables for AWS credentials
- Build process:
  - Install dependencies (Ruby gems)
  - Build Jekyll site (`jekyll build`)
  - Test build output
  - Deploy to S3
  - Invalidate CloudFront

## Environment Management
- **Development (dev)**:
  - Deploy from `develop` or `dev` branch
  - Use dev S3 bucket and CloudFront distribution
  - May include draft content and debug information
- **Production (prod)**:
  - Deploy from `main` or `master` branch
  - Use production S3 bucket and CloudFront distribution
  - Optimized, minified assets
  - No debug information
  - Production-ready content only
  - allow seach robots scan production version only (robots.txt)

## File Organization
- Keep configuration files at root level
- Organize assets logically (images, CSS, JS)
- Use includes for reusable components
- Separate concerns (layout, content, styling)
- Document custom configurations

## Security & Performance
- Use environment variables for sensitive data
- Optimize images (WebP format where possible)
- Minify CSS and JavaScript in production
- Enable CloudFront compression
- Use HTTPS everywhere (SSL/TLS)
- Implement proper caching headers

## Testing & Quality Assurance
- Test locally with `jekyll serve` before committing
- Validate HTML markup
- Check Ukrainian language content for typos
- Verify all links and assets load correctly
- Test deployment process in dev before prod

## Documentation
- Keep README.md updated with setup instructions
- Document custom Jekyll configurations
- Document deployment process
- Include environment setup instructions

## When Writing Code
- Ensure proper character encoding in all files
- Consider right-to-left layouts if needed

## Common Tasks
- Adding new pages: Create in root or appropriate directory, add to navigation
- Adding products: Create product pages with consistent structure
- Updating content: Edit markdown files
- Deploying: Push to appropriate branch, CI/CD handles deployment
- Debugging: Use `jekyll serve --verbose` for detailed output

## Dependencies Management
- Use `Gemfile` for Ruby dependencies
- Pin Jekyll version
- Document all plugins and their purposes
- Keep dependencies up to date (security updates)
- Use `bundle install` for dependency management

